{"TopicId":163350,"ForumId":32,"TopicTitle":"Delta-V formula?","CreatedByName":"Xyphos","CreatedById":139010,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-07-17T11:49:15Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"Xyphos","CreatedById":139010,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-07-17T11:49:15Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nWhat\u0027s the math formula to compute the Delta-V required to reach full orbit around a specific celestial body from it\u0027s surface, including atmospheric pressure, if applicable?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nsure, I could look at the cheat-sheat chart, but I wanna know the formula.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222017-07-17T11:50:08Z\u0022 title=\u002207/17/2017 11:50  AM\u0022 data-short=\u00226 yr\u0022\u003EJuly 17, 2017\u003C/time\u003E by Xyphos\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"StarStreak2109","CreatedById":118557,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-07-17T11:55:16Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delta-v\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delta-v\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"KerbMav","CreatedById":70338,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-07-17T11:55:19Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nMaybe you will find here what you are looking for:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ciframe data-embedcontent=\u0022\u0022 frameborder=\u00220\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?/topic/36264-how-to-calculate-deltav-to-get-to-orbit-or-to-get-from-orbit-to-land/\u0026amp;do=embed\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Xyphos","CreatedById":139010,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-07-17T11:56:27Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223123338\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022163350\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221500292519\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002270338\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022KerbMav\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n1 minute ago, KerbMav said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nMaybe you will find here what you are looking for:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nthat works, thanks!\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Xyphos","CreatedById":139010,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-07-17T12:16:44Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nnew question: what if the body is tidally locked? does that still count as rotation?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Kyle Worden","CreatedById":179715,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-07-17T12:24:13Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223123345\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022163350\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221500293804\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022139010\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Xyphos\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\nJust now, Xyphos said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nnew question: what if the body is tidally locked? does that still count as rotation?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nYes, a tidally locked body is still rotation, Lets look at the Mun for example. It\u0027s semi-major axis is 12,000km and has an orbital period of 138,984s. Now since the Mun is tidally locked, its rotational period is the same as its orbital period.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSo, since the Mun\u0027s radius is 200km, we can find the circumference at the equator of about 1,256,640m.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nTaking distance over time to find rotational velocity we get (1,256,640(m) / 138,984(s)) this equals a surface velocity of 9.04 m/s\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Xyphos","CreatedById":139010,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-07-17T12:26:06Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223123347\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022163350\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221500294253\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022179715\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Kyle Worden\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n1 minute ago, Kyle Worden said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nto find rotational velocity we get (1,256,640(m) / 138,984(s)) this equals a surface velocity of 9.04 m/s\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nperfect. awesome. thanks\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"suicidejunkie","CreatedById":155878,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-07-17T17:04:06Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nYou can also find that value by landing, and then clicking the navball over to show orbital speed instead of surface speed.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe exact value will vary by how close you are to the equator and the altitude of the terrain you\u0027re on.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"}]}